Thanks to the advantage of the hydrothermal method, the temperature here is high enough to push the GLU was carbonized and results in “carbon core”, as reflected by the TEM image and the XRD pattern (Fig. 1
                        a), while the temperature can not supply enough power to broken all MH down, as reflected by the FTIR spectrum (Fig. 1b) and the high nitrogen content. The carbon core appears clearly in TEM images with size sitting in 2–6 nm which are almost amorphous. The XRD pattern belonging to the N-CDots show a broad peak centered at about 2θ = 23° which is consistent with most of the reported studies revealing the amorphous carbon phase [29,30]. Excepting the OH groups appearing at 3150–3400 cm−1 [31] which are from the partial carbonized GLU, CN (1616 cm−1 [32]) and CN (1413 cm−1 [33]) groups are appeared obviously which are from the MH. The MH performs mainly as a passivation layer outside the carbon core. The N/C molar ration reach to 39.9%. The N-CDots were proved to be a nearly spherical carbon nanoparticles functionalized by an organic shell composed of OH and a rich of nitrogen-containing groups and MH molecules (Fig. 2
                        ).
